      "stem_html": "<p><i>N</i>-Phenylsydnone, so-named because it was first studied at the University of Sydney, Australia, behaves like a typical aromatic molecule. Explain, using the Hückel 4<i>n</i> + 2 rule.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBa0FWIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--5406e4fc696bd761a9f2867cb1476bf338113c10/OChem_15_EC_019.jpg\" alt=\"Two interconvertible structures of N-phenylsydnone. In both structures, the nitrogen atom bonded to the benzene ring has a positive charge.\">",
